body:
@thlorenz for the use case of wanting to disable module level transforms lets say I have several components all as CommonJS npm modules, and each of those uses coffeescript. Currently browserify (and correct me if I'm wrong) requires me to add `coffeeify` as a module level transform so when I require in those modules into a parent project they can be correctly transformed. But now I want to also add code coverage for my coffee files using [Ibrik](https://github.com/HBOCodeLabs/ibrik). When I add the coverage using Ibrik it will convert my coffee files to JS, so I no longer need to use the coffeeify transform. Unfortunately there is no way for me to stop browserify from applying the module level transform and I get an error as coffeeify attempts to parse `.coffee` files that are actually at this point javascript. My current line of thinking involved making my own coffeeify transform where I could set an option whether to add the Ibrik coverage or not. This still wouldn't be possible using the `package.json` example though since I only get one chance to configure how I want that transform to work.

What is difficult about this situation is that I need to include coffeeify in my `package.json` but I have no way to actually disable or override it. Like I mentioned, exposing a `transformKey` option through the api would let me disable all module transforms, but I don't think that's the best answer.

As far as the current way transforms are handled, while the simplicity of them might make them reusable in different scenarios, in use I feel like I'm not getting as much out of them as I want. In a single project I could want to perform various transforms to my code for development vs. production vs. testing.

@thlorenz I think currently for transforms that only need to be configured once using `package.json` is fine. As soon as you need to configure the transform conditionally (lets say a different config for testing vs. production), then storing that config in a static file becomes a problem.

The way I see it you have:
- Everything in `package.json` is what you want to use when the module is consumed, IE required into a project
- Those settings in `package.json` should be allowed to be overridden or ignored so you can use different options when in development or testing etc

So if you were to use the browserify api (like tools such as grunt-browserify and karma-browserify make use of) you could do something like:

```
var options = { ignoreModuleTranforms: true },
    b = browerify(options);

b.transform("transformify", {someOption: true})
```

Browserify could pass those options onto module deps and could then do something simple like execute the transform using the context of the options object passed into it, so you could then have a transform like:

```
function transformify(file) {
  if (this.someOption) {

  }
}
```

@colinkahn the only way that this stays backwards compat with all tools that consume the transform field (maybe more than just browserify) and simple, is to specify options as follows:

``` json
{
"browserify": {
  "transform": [ "coffeeify", "ngtemplatefy" ],
   "transform-options": { "ngtemplatefy": { "module": "mod" } }
 }
}
```

That way `"transform"` field stays dead simple but an advanced feature exists.

@thlorenz I think if some transform is "configurable" then it can expose a function which returns a configured transform stream as I illustrated above (`makeTransformify`). Package author who wants to use such transform with some custom configuration can just create a module (`_transform-this.js` for example) inside a package with configured transform:

```
var makeTransformify = require('transformify').makeTransformify;
module.exports = makeTransformify({someOption: null});
```

and specify it in `package.json`:

```
...
"browserify": {
  "transform": [ "coffeeify", "./_transform_this.js" ]
}
...
```

Why is changing the transform signature a problem?  If we change it to:

function ({String} file, {obj} options) -> {TransformStream}

So long as transforms take into account the condition where `options` is null, then they'll continue to behave well when used in other modules?

If you can hold out a bit I'm planning on writing a transform that itself picks transforms according to your environment.
With it you could do in your `package.json`:

``` json
{ 
"browserify": {
  "transform": [ "some transform that applies in all envs", "config-transform" ]
},
"config-transform": {
  "prod": [ "transform to run in prod only" ],
  "dev": [ "requirefy" ],
  "test": [ "test-inject" ]
}
}
```

This is the rough idea I have so far. That `config-transform` would basically just resolve the appropriate transforms depending on an environment variable, and run the content through each of them for each file.
To browserify it will look like the transformations are done by the `config-transform` itself.

Any feedback regarding this idea is appreciated here.

@thlorenz excited to hear this! My question is, in application, lets say I have a project that uses several modules, all with `config-transform` in their `package.json`. When I browserify the project, I wouldn't necessarily want the other modules that use `config-transform` to also pick up on the environment variable, since that could compile them in some unwanted way. Instead I'd want them to behave much like transforms do now for modules, using their `module` level transform. Get what I mean? So even though I'm developing on my project, I want the modules to be transformed in some consistent manner when they're required in. Perhaps something like a `module` key would be possible:

```
{ 
"browserify": {
  "transform": [ "some transform that applies in all envs", "config-transform" ]
},
"config-transform": {
  "module": ["when this module is required, use this transform"],
  "prod": [ "transform to run in prod only" ],
  "dev": [ "requirefy" ],
  "test": [ "test-inject" ]
}
}
```

Just a suggestion, but then you'd be able to really pinpoint the behavior when you're using a lot of different components.
